1 Description of results

  • Outcomes of interest included 6 continious and 1 binary traits.
  • We tested for association only 37,000 clean and long ancestry segements.
  • We fited linear models (OLS)
    • No PCs were included as covariates.
    • No random effects.

1.1 Correction of inflation

The test statistics from association analysis had substatial inflation. We applied correction based on the lambda value.

The observed median value of the chi-squared statistic for the null markers divided by the expected median value of the chi-squared statistic (approximately 0.456 for 1 df tests) is the inflation factor, lambda. If lambda is less than or equal to 1, no adjustment is necessary. When lambda is greater than one, all subsequent chi-squared statistics on a set of candidate markers are divided by lambda.

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3133943/

Our code:

function(pvals, ...)
{
  stats <- qchisq(pvals, 1, lower.tail = FALSE)
  
  inflation <- median(stats, na.rm = TRUE) / qchisq(0.5, 1)
  
  ### correction
  pvals_corrected <- pvals
  if(inflation > 1) {
    stats_corrected <- stats / inflation
    pvals_corrected <- pchisq(stats_corrected, 1, lower.tail = FALSE)
  }
  
  return(pvals_corrected)
}
<environment: namespace:qq>

1.2.1 Bonferroni threshold

0.05 / 32e3
[1] 1.5625e-06
  • None of association signals per traits survives the multiple-testing correction.
  • The Bonferroni threshold is conservative for our (corelated) tests.

  attributes = c('ensembl_gene_id', 'hgnc_symbol', 'chromosome_name', 'start_position', 'end_position'),

4 Results

  • Figure on the left: qq-plot of p-values coming from linear models
  • Figure on the left: corrected p-values
  • Table of the top signals was produced as follows:
    1. filter out associations with p-values above 0.001
    2. take only top 5 associations from each chromosome
    3. sort p-values
    4. note that some p-values can be lost, but the highest p-values per each chromosome are shown
